AB  - Since the widespread availability of generative Artificial Intelligence (AI) Chatbots, colleges and universities have been grappling with their impact on higher education. The attitudes toward AI Chatbots vary greatly, but most studies focus on specific campus populations. As such, we designed and conducted a survey to capture use and perception of AI Chatbots across the three primary campus populations: faculty (N = 77), staff (N = 110), and students (N = 223). While all three campus populations had similar scores regarding being first adopter of new technology, they had statistically significantly different scores for seven other 5-point Likert scales regarding AI Chatbot use and perception. Despite the differences in their use and perception, subsequent textual analysis indicates that the campus populations share similar concerns about AI Chatbot accuracy, bias, and technology dependency. As such, we provide insight into the attitudes across campus after a sudden and significant technological innovation disrupts educational practices. © 2025 International Association for Computer Information Systems.
