AB  - Underlying thousands of studies on technology adoption is the truism that people make the decision to adopt based on experiences. However, emerging research suggests that memory of those experiences offers an alternative explanation for adoption. Given the little attention placed on the role of the memory of experience in technology adoption, this research explores the phenomenon empirically. Drawing on the technology acceptance model and the theory of planned behavior, this study understands adoption based on individuals’ present beliefs, present attitudes, plus the memory of experiences with the technology, within the context of generative artificial intelligence (AI). The results show that, in addition to the present belief and attitude perspective, the memory of experiences perspective can contribute to technology adoption, while the memory of experiences can significantly influence present beliefs and present attitudes. Our findings entail important implications for practice on promoting technology adoption and providing actionable design strategies. © 2025 Taylor & Francis Group, LLC.
