AB  - The use of ChatGPT as an effective learning tool in higher education is emerging. With the significant prevalence of social media, students’ attitudes and behaviours encounter impact derived from social media influencers. There is a necessity to consider students’ acceptance towards ChatGPT under the potential effect from such channels. By utilising an extended UTAUT2 model, this study reveals the positive effect of performance expectancy, effort expectancy, social influence, habit, learning value and personal innovativeness on students’ intention to use ChatGPT in their studies. This research also clarifies the pivotal role of social media influencers’ expertise as a moderator. Findings highlight the external influence and interplay effect of new learning trends, in which students incorporate social media to generate advice on the adoption of ChatGPT. © 2025 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group.
