AB  - This study investigates the adoption of generative artificial intelligence (GenAI) among Chinese business school students by integrating the Information Adoption Model (IAM) and the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM). Specifically, it examines how argument quality, source credibility, perceived ease of use (PEU), and expertise shape students' perceived usefulness (PU), behavioral intention (BI), and actual use of GenAI. Using survey data collected from 672 business school students and analyzed through Partial Least Squares Structural Equation Modeling (PLS-SEM), the results indicate that PEU, argument quality, and source credibility significantly enhance PU, which in turn positively influences students’ intention to adopt GenAI. Behavioral intention demonstrates strong predictive power for actual use, reaffirming the intention–behavior linkage central to TAM. The findings further reveal that expertise positively moderates the relationship between argument quality and PU, suggesting that more knowledgeable students are better equipped to evaluate the substantive strength of AI-generated outputs. Multigroup analyses show that gender, educational level, and prior AI experience significantly moderate key structural relationships. Female students place greater emphasis on PEU when forming usefulness perceptions, while students with prior AI experience rely more heavily on argument quality in evaluating PU. Moreover, female students, postgraduate students, and those with prior AI experience exhibit stronger intention–actual use relationships compared to male students, undergraduates, and students without prior AI experience, respectively. By integrating IAM and TAM in the GenAI context, this study provides a theoretically grounded explanation of how information evaluation processes translate into technology adoption behaviors. Practically, the findings offer actionable insights for policymakers and educators seeking to promote responsible and effective GenAI adoption, highlighting the importance of tailoring strategies to different student demographics and experience levels. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd
