DO  - 10.1080/10447318.2025.2565399
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105018013209?origin=resultslist
AD  - College of Economics and Management, Shandong University of Science and Technology, Qingdao, China
AB  - Generative artificial intelligence (GAI) promises to transform workplace productivity, yet its adoption faces an intriguing paradox: higher-ranked employees, despite greater technical literacy, resist GAI. This contradicts the view that education and rank positively correlate with technology acceptance. To address this gap, this study extends the Unified Theory of Acceptance and Use of Technology (UTAUT) by introducing a dual-identification mechanism, treating organizational levels and educational attainment as moderators. Using data from 315 employees across 24 Chinese provinces, analyzed through Partial Least Squares Structural Equation Modeling (PLS-SEM), the study provides context-specific insights into GAI adoption in digital transformation. The findings show standardized implementation is ineffective across ranks: higher-ranked employees adopt GAI more when perceiving high performance expectations and low effort; social influence impacts senior management significantly, while technical support and reduced barriers matter for junior staff. These results highlight the need for stratified, position-specific GAI strategies, especially in hierarchical organizations. © 2025 Taylor & Francis Group, LLC.
