AB  - This study proposes a novel multi-stage framework for identifying high-potential technology startups (TSs). It integrates technology opportunity discovery with multi-source data analytics to mitigate information asymmetry in venture capital decision-making. The framework comprises three integrated stages: 1) Technology community division: utilizing Large Language Models and an innovative graph embedding model (PatGraph) to cluster patent citation networks into distinct technology communities; 2) Technology opportunity discovery: applying the Search Path Count algorithm, semantic expansion, and the Consolidating/Disruptive index to uncover both incremental and disruptive innovation opportunities; 3) TSs evaluation: constructing a multi-dimensional “technology-market-team” system evaluated via a combined weighting-TOPSIS approach to rank TSs. The framework is corroborated by a case study in China's unmanned aerial vehicle flight control domain. The case study identified 73 high-potential TSs across seven technology communities. Communities associated with flight safety control, specialized configurations, and flight simulation have emerged as the most potential avenues for investment. This study presents a systematic “community-opportunity-entity” analytical framework that amalgamates patent text analytics with enterprise data for TS identification. It provides a scalable, AI-driven decision-support instrument for venture capitalists (VCs) and policymakers. The framework enhances the objectivity, granularity, and interpretability of TS screening processes, especially in patent-intensive emerging industries. © 2026 Elsevier Inc.
